Based on the Russian RPK light machine gun, the NHM features a stronger receiver and a longer, thicker-profile chrome-lined barrel measuring 20 inches  along with a forward-mounted steel bipod.

Like the RPK, the NHM-91 utilizes a heavier-gauge stamped sheet metal receiver built from 1.5mm-thick stamped sheet metal instead of the 1mm thickness typical of a Soviet or Chinese-made AKM, resulting in increased rigidity, heavier weight, and improved overall accuracy. The longer, heavier barrel reduces shot dispersion and gives the NHM-91 a longer sight radius, again resulting in improved accuracy over the typical semi-auto AKM. Trigger pull weight is also lighter than other AK designs, and some users report the rifle capable of 2-2.5 minutes of angle accuracy or better with factory 7.62x39mm ammunition.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt M4 w 14.5" pinned A2x (Must Click) w Nikon scope and more
location: Bradenton (or Tampa or St. Pete), Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
I have a pretty bad @$$ carbine that needs a new home because I mainly use my SBRs. I'm mostly looking to trade it for a .308 or .223 bolt gun (like a Remington 700 STS Tactical) or sell it for enough to buy a .308 bolt gun. Also, I can do a trade plus cash from me if you have a Rem 700 w a scope.  

The upper:
The upper on this M4 is all-Colt. It has a Colt flat top upper w feed ramps and the rare and sought after Diemaco "D" (Canadian Colt) forge mark. The barrel is the same barrel our troops are issued; a Colt NATO Govt. profile 14.5" w 1/7 twist rate. I had a BCM A2x (extended A2) flash hider professionally installed to bring it to a legal 16" to make it legal.  It has a Knights Armament RAS rail and a Knights Armament handstop with QD swivel. I'm also throwing in a Knights Armament vertical grip. I have less than 500rds on this barrel. The bore is super perfect.  

The scope on this is a Nikon P223 (designed specifically for AR-15s) with super sexy turrets and the scope rings are Weaver Tactical high-rise scope rings. This thing sits at a perfect height and gives a crisp field of view perfect for close range use and for slightly longer defensive ranges too.   

Oh and there's a mMidWest Industries sling mount clamped around the buffer tube. That's yours too. 


The lower:
The lower is an Anderson stripped lower with a Daniel Defense lower parts kit (professionally installed) and a Daniel Defense buffer tube, Daniel Defense buffer and an LMT SOPMOD stock. Yes, I know, "Anderson", but I have a Colt lower too that I can swap (and paint to match) but it'll raise the price by another $600.00 and this Anderson stripped lower is every bit as well-built as any Colt lower I've ever had and the Daniel Defense parts kit inside it works great; nice trigger and everything operates smooth. 

There is currently an A2 grip on it but I can put a Tango Down grip on it if you'd prefer that (it is painted to match) and I'll include the USGI mag that is painted to match as well.  If you don't want the scope (you'd be a crazy person because this scope is actually fantastic) I'll swap it out for a Colt carry handle instead.   

Anyway, this M4 is as close to an authentic M4 as you're going to find and the fact that I built the lower on an Anderson (during the "big scare" when no other lowers were available) means that it's way more affordable than it otherwise would be.

Selling my twice fired model year 2008 Ruger Model KP95PR (*DC) as I have just been informed by my significant other that I might be just a tad obsessive compulsive when it comes to being a firearms enthusiast.  It has only taken her 6 months, but I am finally caving.  In order to reduce any cognitive dissonance on my end, I have convinced myself that I really need to do it in order to make room for my remaining collection. I might be selling a few other firearms in addition to the couple that I have posted thus far, it is just easier said than done...as I am sure many other enthusiasts can understand the situation. Anyhoo, here are the gun stats:

K=Stainless Steel
P95=9mm Model
PR=Picatinny Rail 
DC=De-cocker Option

Comes with 3 factory original 15 round magazines in 9mm, along with loader and everything you see pictured with the case (minus the bullets as it served more as a "bedroom nightstand" firearm than in the safe, however always remained in the case).  Being that my 1st handgun I had ever owned was a Ruger P89 9mm, I had been already familiar with this platform therefore the low round count as a visual inspection will reveal as much).  There is not so much as a single blemish on this gun, it is as new as the day it was originally purchased. Buyer will NOT be disappointed.

Some quick facts regarding this particular firearm:

The P95PR was introduced in 2005, it incorporates a Picatinny rail into the frame and adds a new non-slip texturing in the polymer frame. This model replaced the original P95 in production.

In December 2004, Ruger was awarded a contract for 5,000 KP95D pistols by the U.S. Army Tank-automotive and Armaments Command, Rock Island Arsenal, Illinois.[6]

The P95 was slowly phased out in recent years in favor of the newer SR series. Eventually, the P95 was quietly discontinued in October 2013 and removed from Ruger's website catalog.

The P-Series is NO LONGER in production as it has been replaced by the SR-Series.  Here is a chance to own a very like new example that has been referenced to as one of the most dependable & reliable pistols made as they will shoot anything you feed it whether steel or brass. Thank you.
